commit.message:
readme: Fix FI18 in table of error codes

Looks like a copy-and-paste went unedited.
Release 0.4.6
Removed Python 3.3 support in Travis CI
Manually download files

Add "annotation" feature

Python 3.7 introduced "annotations" feature. See
https://docs.python.org/3/whatsnew/3.7.html#pep-563-postponed-evaluation-of-annotations

Update the version number in the readme

The last two releases weren't updating the version number, fixed now.

Fix formatting in README

The code markup in the newer change logs wasn't using the correct markup. It
is also trying to describe the change in version 0.4.3 better.
Release 0.4.5

Add LICENSE and tests to source distribution (#14)

The source distribution now contains the LICENSE and test file to aid
packaging.

Add support for pip version 10 (#17)

With pip 10 it moved all external API into internal API packages, because they
don't actually provide an API. Instead of just redirecting to the new package
it is now actually using `pkg_resources` like the `pip` package.

Also add a test specifically for pip 10 under Python 3.5.

Even though `flake8` is installed at the beginning due to the `setup.py` file,
it actually isn't correctly installed for the test later. With `pip`'s
function it would install the plugin and this would also install `flake8`
again. By manually installing it beforehand this is prevented.

Run coverage on all builds including nightly

When the nightly was Python 3.6 the coverage test failed, but that is now
fixed, so the exclusion is no longer necessary.

Remove special case for Python 2.6

As Flake8 does not support Python 2.6, and there hasn't been a test on Python
2.6 with this plugin, the special case can be removed.

Add support for Python 3.6 and run tests on it

It should already support Python 3.6, so add them and run tests on it.

Only generate message in the function

When it generates the error, the line number and column offset are just passed
along. So instead of generating the tuple in the function do it when it
actually yields the value.
Fix typo in README
Release 0.4.4

Add a framework classifier

Warehouse (pypi.org) allows search results to be filtered by trove classifiers.
One such classifier is `Framework`, which accepts `Flake8` as a value. Setting
the classifier should help people find flake8-comprehensions when searching for
flake8 plugins.

Upgrade setuptools according to Flake8 requirement

Flake8 now requires setuptools to be at least version 30, but some Python
versions come installed with an older version and so we need to manually
update it before we can actually run the tests.

Revert "Make offset consistent with flake8 version 3"

This reverts commit eaf2799f41ca3a5692fed2df4dfbc06b0627dcfe.
download latest 3.6, for more stable tests
Release 0.4.3

Use correct configuration name

Previously it used the option name without the preceding dashes but in
3243bf40 it also replaced dashes inside the name with underscores. This
reverts the change in behaviour.
Release 0.4.2

Allow other error codes in tests

Instead of failing if an error code not from this plugin pops up, it should
just ignore them. This is necessary because now `pyflakes` also complains
about invalid imports using `F999` code. As long as it is not clear if `FI90`
should be removed, it should still test it.

Use file suffix to tests using flake8 itself

With version 3 of flake8 it only tests file which end in `.py`, so the
temporary file must use that suffix as well.

Make offset consistent with flake8 version 3

With version 3 of flake8 the offset starts at `0` instead of `1`. The stand
alone version would previously output `1` but will now also output `0`.

The tests reflect that and will use the correct indentation depending on the
installed version of `flake8`.

Make `reverse_parse` a method

Instead of having the function at module level it needs to be a method of a
`TestCase` class because it uses `self`, but no call actually used that code
so it wasn't detected yet.

Indent installation output in flake8 test

When installing flake8 it should highlight what is actually output from the
installation. So it adds a newline after it and indents each line of output.

Support flake8 version 3

With version 3 of flake8 it removed the `config_options` attribute and changed
it to a custom keyword argument. This is providing support for both variants
by first trying the call with the keyword argument and then, if it fails, by
removing that keyword argument and manually adding the option to
`config_options`.
Release 0.4.1
